ce:section.ce:para:
The photocatalyic activity of the product was studied by degradation of six dyes namely Acid Blue, Acid Red, Methylene Blue, Methyl Orange, Eosin Y and Eriochrome Black T. The results showed that the synthesized N-CQD had high photocatalytic activity and they can decompose the selected dyes in the minimum possible time that is mainly due to produce of reactive oxide species (ROS) in the aqueous medium. Acid blue was decomposed completely after 30 min irradiation (Fig. 9
                        ). As can be seen, the concentration of this pigment become zero in presence of N-CQD as photocatalyst under ultraviolet irradiation. Another dye studied in this work was Acid Red (Fig. 10
                        ). The results showed by ultraviolet radiation, the dye decolorated completely only after 30 min. Eosin Y was the other dye decomposed completely after 90 min (Fig. 11
                        ). Methylen blue was also decomposed after 90 min radiation in presence of the photocatalyst (Fig. 12
                        ). Decomposition of all dyes follow from the radical mechanism degradation of their parts in presence of reactive oxide species produced from UV radiation to the water. The results also showed the synthesized N-CQD can decompose under visible radiation. In other words, it is also a visible photocatalyst. As can be observed, Eriochrome black T (Fig. 13
                        ) and methyl orange (Fig. 14
                        ) are two dyes that decomposed completely without any radiation and immediately after pouring them two the dye solution. it can be said due to synthesized CQD has a low band gap (1.94 eV), they can excite only under visible radiation and produce electrons and holes to creation the reactive oxide species. The effects of dose, pH and contact time were investigated on the degradation of Acid blue under ultraviolet irradiation. The results are shown in Fig. 15
                        . As it can be seen the degradation rate of the dye was decreased by changing the pH of the dye solution (Fig. 15a). Based on the obtained results it can be said by increasing the number of H+ and OH− in the dye solution, the production rate of reactive oxide species is decreased and hence the decomposition rate of dye molecules is reduced. The contact time effect on the dye decomposition was also investigated. As it was mentioned previously, Acid blue dye was completely decomposed after 30 min. therefore, 10 min and 20 min irradiation times were selected to investigate the contact time on the dye decomposition. As shown in Fig. 15b, the dye concentration was decreased after 20 min but the dye molecules were completely decomposed after 30 min. In fact after 30 min UV irradiation the ROS concentration is as high as it can decompose all the dye molecules. The effect of nanoparticles dose on the dye molecules degradation was investigated. For this purpose, the nanoparticles amount was fixed, and the dye concentration was increased two and three times. The results showed that due to the huge surface of the synthesized quantum dots, they can decompose more dye molecules (Fig. 15c and d). It was also found that to decompose the dye structure with more concentration, more time is needed to produce enough ROS amount. It can be concluded that the product has high photocatalytic activity and it can decolorate various dyes under ultraviolet and visible radiations. Scheme 2
                         shows a schematic of degradation of the selected dyes in presence of N-CQD under irradiation. As it can be seen in Scheme 2, when the quantum dots were exposed under ultraviolet irradiation, electron-hole pairs were created that they can produce the reactive oxide species (ROS) such as H2O2 and OH− in the aqueous medium. The produced ROS attack to the dye molecules and decompose them from a radical mechanism. For example, when the ROS attack to the Acid blue, N2 molecule is released and hence the dye structure is completely decomposed.

Due to the huge surface area of the N-CQD, the surface adsorption ability of the product was examined by removing Cd2+ and Pb2+ heavy metal ions from the water. The results showed the product has a high surface activity that can adsorb these two heavy metal ions on its particles surfaces. As shown in this figure, the product can adsorb 37% of Cd2+ (Fig. 16
                        ) and 75% of Pb2+ (Fig. 17
                        ) form the aqueous solution. In fact, each small particle can adsorb each ion, potentially.
